    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-04-22T04:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-04-22T04:00:00-05:00" n="165"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d165">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 861.00/1634</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_MRS1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Morris</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-04-22T18:00:00+09:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 22, 1918, 6 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 9.25 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Referring to my cable of April 13, 2 a.m.,<note n="1" xml:id="d165fn1">
                        <ref target="frus1918Russiav02#pg_122">Vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>, p.
                            122</ref>.</note> and suggestion of <persName corresp="#p_MTG1"
                        >Masaryk</persName>
                    <note n="2" xml:id="d165fn2">
                        <persName corresp="#p_MTG1">Thomas G. Masaryk</persName>, President of the
                        Czecho-Slovak National Council.</note> to organize corporation for purchase
                    and distribution of wheat in Russia. I have to-day conferred at length with
                    Major <persName>Fitzwilliams</persName> of the British Army, who has been in
                    Rumania, Ukraine, Moscow, and Siberia. He confirms <persName corresp="#p_MTG1"
                        >Masaryk</persName>’s [statements?] fully and is in accord with his
                    conclusions except as to the necessity or advisability of immediate <hi
                        rend="italic">de facto</hi> recognition of Bolshevik government and
                    possibility of organizing Russian Army. He particularly emphasizes need of
                    Russian people for manufactured articles: shoes, household utensils, farming
                    implements, textiles and clothes of all kinds. He strongly advocates <persName
                        corresp="#p_MTG1">Masaryk</persName>’s plan of corporation financed by
                    Allied Governments to purchase such articles and exchange them for wheat, which
                    could be resold in famine districts, particularly large cities. Such plan (1)
                    would prevent large quantities of hoarded wheat eventually falling into enemy’s
                    hands, (2) would form economic foundation for Allied propaganda, (3) would
                    create better understanding with liberal movement in Russia without involving
                    official recognition of Bolshevik government, (4) would offer a constructive
                    alternative to military intervention.</p>
                <p>I am reliably informed that Japanese manufacturers have adequate stocks of goods
                    needed, particularly shoes and textiles. I believe Japanese Government would
                    consider favorably close cooperation in such a plan. Goods could be bought here,
                    shipped by way of Dairen to Harbin, and handled with the aid of <persName
                        corresp="#p_SJF1">Stevens</persName>’s<note n="3" xml:id="d165fn3">
                        <persName corresp="#p_SJF1">John F. Stevens</persName>, chairman of the
                        Advisory Commission of Railway Experts to Russia.</note> contingent. Their
                    transportation could be placed in the hands of <persName corresp="#p_SJF1"
                        >Stevens</persName>, and, if understanding were reached informally [with]
                    Bolshevik government, it would be possible to place <persName corresp="#p_SJF1"
                        >Stevens</persName>’s men on Trans-Siberian Baikal Railway and even further
                    west.</p>
                <p>This plan would involve approval of Bolshevik leaders, which might be obtained
                    through efforts of <persName corresp="#p_FDR1">Francis</persName> and the
                    cooperation of the Japanese Government, which might see in it a solution of the
                        <pb facs="0171" n="121" xml:id="pg_121"/> intervention problem, and
                    agreement between Allied Governments, thus joining them in a definite
                    constructive policy. While such a plan appears visionary, it has the approval of
                    those familiar with present needs and conditions in Russia. Major
                        <persName>Fitzwilliams</persName> expects to leave here in a few days via
                    Washington and will report to <persName corresp="#p_RE1"
                        >Reading</persName>.<note n="1" xml:id="d165fn4">The <persName
                            corresp="#p_RE1">Earl of Reading</persName>, British Ambassador on
                        Special Mission to the United States.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_MRS1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Morris</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
